  <script>
    const ticket = document.getElementById("ticket");
    const ticketInput = document.getElementById("ticketInput");
    const customers = document.getElementById("customers");
    const customersInput = document.getElementById("customersInput");
    const fivePercent = document.getElementById("fivePercent");
    const tenPercent = document.getElementById("tenPercent");
    const resetBtn = document.getElementById("resetBtn");

    // Retention multipliers
    const RETENTION_5 = 0.05;
    const RETENTION_10 = 0.10;

    function syncInputs(slider, input) {
      slider.addEventListener("input", () => {
        input.value = slider.value;
        calculate();
      });

      input.addEventListener("input", () => {
        slider.value = input.value;
        calculate();
      });
    }

    function calculate() {
      const avgTicket = Math.max(0, Number(ticket.value) || 0);
      const monthlyCustomers = Math.max(0, Number(customers.value) || 0);

      const baseRevenue = avgTicket * monthlyCustomers;
      const fiveBoost = baseRevenue * RETENTION_5;
      const tenBoost = baseRevenue * RETENTION_10;

      fivePercent.textContent = `$${fiveBoost.toLocaleString()}`;
      tenPercent.textContent = `$${tenBoost.toLocaleString()}`;
    }

    function resetCalculator() {
      ticket.value = 75;
      ticketInput.value = 75;
      customers.value = 150;
      customersInput.value = 150;
      calculate();
    }

    syncInputs(ticket, ticketInput);
    syncInputs(customers, customersInput);
    resetBtn.addEventListener("click", resetCalculator);

    calculate();
  </script>
</body>
</html>

The Technical barries fro Gas Stations, Convenience Stores, and Liquor Store Owners

Gas stations, convenience stores, and liquor stores all operate in one of the fastest-paced and margin-sensitive retail environments. Small business owners manage long operating hours, high transaction volumes, thin margins, and constant operational demands. While many software tools promise growth through loyalty programs and digital engagements, adoption remains low in this niche. 

Many store owners rely on old, outdated POS systems, Veeder Root as the common fuel management software, or standalone inventory tools that do not integrate with modern SaaS platforms. Owners are hesitant to introduce new software that might change daily operations or require expert system upgrades. 

Most small business owners in this niche are hands-on, on the floor, managing staff and vendors, and ensuring customer needs are met. They rarely have time to sit down at a computer, watch demos, or interpret a complex dashboard. They already have to deal with various equipment, including the POS system, the Lottery machine, vendor ordering systems, and credit returns. Any tool that requires complex training, configuration, or extended onboarding will most likely be abandoned early on. 

Since store owners are more focused on ensuring a product sells quickly, this translates into a dollar impact. The friction RIO calculator only requires two familiar inputs: average sale per customer and monthly customer volume. These are numbers that the owners already understand and can estimate quickly without pulling up any monthly reports. By translating retention improvements directly into monthly and annual revenue gains, the calculator bridges the gap between abstract loyalty concepts and concrete financial outcomes. Small business owners can immediately see how small changes in customer behavior, product changes, or even an increase in product volume can impact revenue. 

The design of the friction RIO calculator is best for small business owners in this niche because they can use it on the go on their phones without any credentials. The calculator shows a realistic improvement range of 5-10%. This mirrors how owners think about uncertainty, and it can reduce skepticism around overly precise projects. 



